mat/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F09%2F88%2Fc732364d407eae7b658981fff573%2Ftef-miorarajaonary-madagascar-20240918-0020-group-1.jpeg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2000x1125+0+438/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F09%2F88%2Fc732364d407eae7b658981fff573%2Ftef-miorarajaonary-madagascar-20240918-0020-group-1.jpeg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2000x1125+0+438/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F09%2F88%2Fc732364d407eae7b658981fff573%2Ftef-miorarajaonary-madagascar-20240918-0020-group-1.jpeg" class="img" alt="Group portrait (from left to right: former FGS patients RAHAMA Abdallah, RAZANAPARANA Sylvia Suzanie, YOLANDRIE. 18 September 2024, district of Ambanja, Northern Madagascar. " loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Group portrait (from left to right: former FGS patients  RAHAMA Abdallah, RAZANAPARANA Sylvia Suzanie, YOLANDRIE. 18 September 2024, district of Ambanja, Northern Madagascar.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Miora Rajaonary/The End Fund                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Eight women posed as part of a project aimed at raising awareness of female genital schistosomiasis, a disease that an estimated 56 million women and girls, primarily in Africa, suffer from, according to the World Health Organization. This waterborne infection is caused by parasitic worms and is particularly prevalent in areas with limited access to clean water and health care. Women contract the disease when they come into contact with contaminated water while working, bathing, or doing laundry. The infection can lead to serious health issues, including infertility and ectopic pregnancy. It can also mimic the symptoms of sexually transmitted diseases, often resulting in shame and dishonor for those affected. The photo exhibit,&lt;em&gt; Sahy Rano&lt;/em&gt;, is currently on display at the Photoville Festival in Brooklyn, N.Y. Take a look at &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/goats-and-soda/2025/06/21/g-s1-73305/photos-neglected-tropical-disease-madagascar-photoville" target="_blank"&gt;some photos of the courageous women&lt;/a&gt; who participated in this project.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you go&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-74392" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 2384;         --source-height: 1341;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2384x1341+0+172/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F20%2F11%2F493128ef4c478b73e2c5558c4603%2Fp18849-fp961293.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2384x1341+0+172/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F20%2F11%2F493128ef4c478b73e2c5558c4603%2Fp18849-fp961293.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2384x1341+0+172/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F20%2F11%2F493128ef4c478b73e2c5558c4603%2Fp1