Fgettyimages-2220675313.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5565x3710+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6f%2F9f%2Fc999c01340b3999ce06035dba2e6%2Fgettyimages-2220675313.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5565x3710+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6f%2F9f%2Fc999c01340b3999ce06035dba2e6%2Fgettyimages-2220675313.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5565x3710+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6f%2F9f%2Fc999c01340b3999ce06035dba2e6%2Fgettyimages-2220675313.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5565x3710+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6f%2F9f%2Fc999c01340b3999ce06035dba2e6%2Fgettyimages-2220675313.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5565x3710+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6f%2F9f%2Fc999c01340b3999ce06035dba2e6%2Fgettyimages-2220675313.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5565x3710+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6f%2F9f%2Fc999c01340b3999ce06035dba2e6%2Fgettyimages-2220675313.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5565x3710+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6f%2F9f%2Fc999c01340b3999ce06035dba2e6%2Fgettyimages-2220675313.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5565x3710+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6f%2F9f%2Fc999c01340b3999ce06035dba2e6%2Fgettyimages-2220675313.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5565x3710+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6f%2F9f%2Fc999c01340b3999ce06035dba2e6%2Fgettyimages-2220675313.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5565x3710+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6f%2F9f%2Fc999c01340b3999ce06035dba2e6%2Fgettyimages-2220675313.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5565x3710+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6f%2F9f%2Fc999c01340b3999ce06035dba2e6%2Fgettyimages-2220675313.jpg" class="img" alt="The stars and stripes, the national flag of the USA flutters during the FIFA Club World Cup 2025 group E match between CF Monterrey and FC Internazionale Milano at Rose Bowl Stadium on June 17 in Pasadena, California." fetchpriority="high" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 The stars and stripes, the national flag of the USA flutters during the FIFA Club World Cup 2025 group E match between CF Monterrey and FC Internazionale Milano at Rose Bowl Stadium on June 17 in Pasadena, California.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Stu Forster/Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Nearly 250 years ago, the Founding Fathers adopted the Declaration of Independence, severing the 13 colonies' connection to Britain and declaring themselves an independent nation. Since then, Americans have observed July 4 as the birth of the United States, &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/series/g-s1-58328/free-speech-first-amendment" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;debating their freedoms&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt; — and celebrating them. This year, NPR wants to know how freedom has been on your mind leading up to the holiday.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;What does freedom mean to you? How are you observing Independence Day? Share your answers with us, and you could be featured in a special July Fourth edition of the &lt;em&gt;Up First &lt;/em&gt;newsletter. Please submit your responses in the form below by June 27. You can also submit voice memos or photos.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;div id="resg-s1-73711-100" class="bucketwrap statichtml"&gt;             &lt;iframe src="https://npr.formstack.com/forms/what_does_freedom_mean_to_you_" title="Formstack Form" width="100%" height="1200"&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;     &lt;!-- END ID="RESG-S1-73711-100" CLASS="BUCKETWRAP STATICHTML" --&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
